{"id":"1312.1784","submitter":"Petros Souvatzis Dr","authors":"Petros Souvatzis and Anders M. N. Niklasson","title":"First principles molecular dynamics without self-consistent field\n  optimization","comments":"11 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.4862907","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a first principles molecular dynamics approach that is based on\ntime-reversible ex- tended Lagrangian Born-Oppenheimer molecular dynamics\n[Phys. Rev. Lett. 100, 123004 (2008)] in the limit of vanishing self-consistent\nfield optimization. The optimization-free dynamics keeps the computational cost\nto a minimum and typically provides molecular trajectories that closely follow\nthe exact Born-Oppenheimer potential energy surface. Only one single\ndiagonalization and Hamiltonian (or Fockian) costruction are required in each\nintegration time step. The proposed dy- namics is derived for a general\nfree-energy potential surface valid at finite electronic temperatures within\nhybrid density functional theory. Even in the event of irregular functional\nbehavior that may cause a dynamical instability, the optimization-free limit\nrepresents an ideal starting guess for force calculations that may require a\nmore elaborate iterative electronic ground state optimization. Our\noptimization-free dynamics thus represents a flexible theoretical framework for\na broad and general class of ab initio molecular dynamics simulations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 6 Dec 2013 06:44:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 16 Dec 2013 20:46:29 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 9 Jan 2014 06:51:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-18"}
